## Section 3.4 (connection-oriented communication)

- In a connection-oriented communication, two endpoints establish a
- session to transfer data reliably, with error detection and
- reordering of received data.  During the connection establishment
- (3-way handshake), both hosts must identify SCHC with the layer-4
- port number and exchange and agree on the Set of Rules (SoR).
- Through the data transfer, the management of the SoR uses the Yang
- data model as described in the [schc-coreconf-management].  Both
- endpoints must make the same changes to keep the integrity of the
- flow control.
+ In a connection-oriented communication, two Instances establish a
+ Session to transfer data reliably, with error detection and
+ reordering of received data.  During the connection establishment
+ (3-way handshake), both Instances identify SCHC with the layer-4
+ port number (used as a Discriminator) and provision and synchronize
+ the Context (its Set of Rules, SoR).  Through the data transfer, the
+ management of the Context (SoR) uses the YANG data model as described
+ in [schc-coreconf-management].  Both Instances must apply the same
+ changes to keep their Contexts consistent for correct flow control.
# NOTE: "exchange and agree on the SoR" -> "provision and synchronize the
# Context" is the one REQUIRED FOR CONCEPTUAL ALIGNMENT edit (see verdicts.md):
# SCHC Architecture -06 base SCHC assumes no in-band negotiation between the
# compressing and decompressing entities; the outcome (both ends share the
# same SoR) is unchanged.

- The SoR may contain dedicated Rules for Acknowledgements and
- connection termination.
+ The SoR may contain dedicated Rules for Acknowledgements and
+ connection termination.
# (unchanged: SoR and Rules are -06 terms)

## Section 3.6 (identifiers)

- 3.6.  SCHC Port Numbers and protocol number as identifiers
+ 3.6.  SCHC Port Numbers and protocol numbers as Discriminators

- In the current SCHC architecture, the SCHC Stratum Header adds
- signalling information to the SCHC datagram.  It may be fully
- compressed, and it does not add any overhead in that case.  The SCHC
- Stratum Header helps to identify the use of SCHC and selects the
- correct instance and SoR in the SCHC process.  The SCHC Stratum
- Header format includes an identifier that depends on the compressed
- stack layer.  These identifiers are the protocol number at layer
- three and port numbers at layer four.
+ In the SCHC architecture [schc-architecture], the identifier used to
+ recognise SCHC is a Discriminator, and any additional signalling
+ carried in band with the SCHC Datagram is a Control Header.  A Control
+ Header may be fully compressed, and it does not add any overhead in
+ that case.  Together, the Discriminator and any Control Header help to
+ identify the use of SCHC and select the correct Instance (and thereby
+ its Context and SoR) in the SCHC process.  The Discriminator depends on
+ the compressed stack layer: it is the protocol number at layer three
+ and the port number at layer four.

